Session outline: Pandas¶

  • Introduction to Pandas Series object
  • Pandas indexing
  • DataFrames
  • Getting data into / out of Pandas
  • Data Cleansing
  • Handling time series data
  • Aggregation and grouping
  • Merging, joining, and concatenating

What is Pandas, anyway?¶

Panel data

  • Uses Numpy for efficient data access & manipulation
  • Adds labels and indexes for ease of use
  • Series and DataFrame are the two core classes in Pandas

Pandas Series¶

The pandas.Series object is like a 1-D array with an index.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd

x = pd.Series([1,2,3,4,5])
x
Out[1]:
0    1
1    2
2    3
3    4
4    5
dtype: int64
In [2]:
(x * 5) + x
Out[2]:
0     6
1    12
2    18
3    24
4    30
dtype: int64
In [3]:
pd.Series([1,2,3,4,5], dtype=float)
Out[3]:
0    1.0
1    2.0
2    3.0
3    4.0
4    5.0
dtype: float64
In [4]:
import numpy as np
In [5]:
np.float128
Out[5]:
numpy.float128
In [6]:
pd.Series([1,2,'hello'])
Out[6]:
0        1
1        2
2    hello
dtype: object
In [7]:
data = pd.Series([1.0, 2, 3, 4, 5])
data
Out[7]:
0    1.0
1    2.0
2    3.0
3    4.0
4    5.0
dtype: float64
In [8]:
data[3] = 3.14
data
Out[8]:
0    1.00
1    2.00
2    3.00
3    3.14
4    5.00
dtype: float64
In [9]:
data[3] = 15
data
Out[9]:
0     1.0
1     2.0
2     3.0
3    15.0
4     5.0
dtype: float64

Pandas uses numpy.array objects to store data:

In [10]:
data.values
Out[10]:
array([ 1.,  2.,  3., 15.,  5.])

Pandas indexing¶

To access values (or slices) and Pandas indexes, we can use either the label-based index, or position:

We can use non-integer indexes:

In [11]:
data = pd.Series([1.0, 2, 3, 4, 5], index=['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'])
data
Out[11]:
a    1.0
b    2.0
c    3.0
d    4.0
e    5.0
dtype: float64
In [12]:
data['a']
Out[12]:
1.0
In [13]:
data[0]
Out[13]:
1.0

If we use labels to index, Pandas considers slices inclusive of both bounds:

In [14]:
data['a':'c']
Out[14]:
a    1.0
b    2.0
c    3.0
dtype: float64

Using positions, however, Pandas uses normal Python half-open intervals:

In [15]:
data[0:3]
Out[15]:
a    1.0
b    2.0
c    3.0
dtype: float64

Pandas has several different index types:

In [16]:
data.index
Out[16]:
Index(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'], dtype='object')
In [17]:
pd.Series([0, 1, 2]).index
Out[17]:
RangeIndex(start=0, stop=3, step=1)
In [18]:
data = pd.Series(range(100))
data.index
Out[18]:
RangeIndex(start=0, stop=100, step=1)
In [19]:
data[::20].index
Out[19]:
RangeIndex(start=0, stop=100, step=20)
In [20]:
data[::20][0] = 200
In [24]:
data.head()
Out[24]:
0    200
1      1
2      2
3      3
4      4
dtype: int64
In [22]:
data.tail()
Out[22]:
95    95
96    96
97    97
98    98
99    99
dtype: int64

Datetime indexing¶

In [25]:
from datetime import datetime, date
data = pd.Series(range(300), pd.date_range(date.today(), periods=300, freq='1D'))
data.head()
Out[25]:
2019-03-22    0
2019-03-23    1
2019-03-24    2
2019-03-25    3
2019-03-26    4
Freq: D, dtype: int64
In [26]:
data.index
Out[26]:
DatetimeIndex(['2019-03-22', '2019-03-23', '2019-03-24', '2019-03-25',
               '2019-03-26', '2019-03-27', '2019-03-28', '2019-03-29',
               '2019-03-30', '2019-03-31',
               ...
               '2020-01-06', '2020-01-07', '2020-01-08', '2020-01-09',
               '2020-01-10', '2020-01-11', '2020-01-12', '2020-01-13',
               '2020-01-14', '2020-01-15'],
              dtype='datetime64[ns]', length=300, freq='D')
In [27]:
data[::30].index
Out[27]:
DatetimeIndex(['2019-03-22', '2019-04-21', '2019-05-21', '2019-06-20',
               '2019-07-20', '2019-08-19', '2019-09-18', '2019-10-18',
               '2019-11-17', '2019-12-17'],
              dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='30D')
In [28]:
from datetime import datetime, date
data = pd.Series(range(300), pd.date_range(datetime.now(), periods=300, freq='17s'))
data.head()
Out[28]:
2019-03-22 16:16:37.583774    0
2019-03-22 16:16:54.583774    1
2019-03-22 16:17:11.583774    2
2019-03-22 16:17:28.583774    3
2019-03-22 16:17:45.583774    4
Freq: 17S, dtype: int64

We can be particularly perverse when using integer-based indexes:

In [29]:
data = pd.Series(range(5), [1, 3, 4, 2, 0])
data
Out[29]:
1    0
3    1
4    2
2    3
0    4
dtype: int64

Label-based indexing with a single value!

In [30]:
data[1]
Out[30]:
0
In [31]:
data[0]
Out[31]:
4

Location-based indexing with slices!

In [32]:
data[0:3]
Out[32]:
1    0
3    1
4    2
dtype: int64

Using .loc and .iloc¶

To eliminate confusion, Pandas gives us explicit indexing via .loc and .iloc

.loc uses label-based indexing .iloc uses location-based ("implicit") indexing

In [33]:
data.loc[0]
Out[33]:
4
In [34]:
data.iloc[0]
Out[34]:
0
In [36]:
data
Out[36]:
1    0
3    1
4    2
2    3
0    4
dtype: int64
In [37]:
data.loc[0:3]
Out[37]:
Series([], dtype: int64)
In [38]:
data.iloc[0:3]
Out[38]:
1    0
3    1
4    2
dtype: int64
In [39]:
data.loc[3:0]
Out[39]:
3    1
4    2
2    3
0    4
dtype: int64

Dict-as-series¶

In [40]:
population = pd.Series({
    'CA': 38332521,
    'TX': 26448193,
    'NY': 19651127,
    'FL': 19552860,
    'IL': 12882135})
population
Out[40]:
CA    38332521
TX    26448193
NY    19651127
FL    19552860
IL    12882135
dtype: int64
In [41]:
population['TX']
Out[41]:
26448193
In [42]:
population['NY': 'IL']
Out[42]:
NY    19651127
FL    19552860
IL    12882135
dtype: int64
In [43]:
population[1:3]
Out[43]:
TX    26448193
NY    19651127
dtype: int64
In [44]:
population.loc['NY': 'IL']
Out[44]:
NY    19651127
FL    19552860
IL    12882135
dtype: int64

Dataframes¶

Pandas also provides a DataFrame object that can be used for 2-D tabular data:

In [45]:
area = pd.Series({
    'CA': 423967, 
    'TX': 695662, 
    'NY': 141297,
    'FL': 170312, 
    'IL': 149995
})
area
Out[45]:
CA    423967
TX    695662
NY    141297
FL    170312
IL    149995
dtype: int64
In [48]:
data = pd.DataFrame({'population': population, 'area': area})
data
Out[48]:
population area
CA 38332521 423967
TX 26448193 695662
NY 19651127 141297
FL 19552860 170312
IL 12882135 149995
In [49]:
data['area']
Out[49]:
CA    423967
TX    695662
NY    141297
FL    170312
IL    149995
Name: area, dtype: int64
In [50]:
data.area
Out[50]:
CA    423967
TX    695662
NY    141297
FL    170312
IL    149995
Name: area, dtype: int64
In [51]:
data[['population']]
Out[51]:
population
CA 38332521
TX 26448193
NY 19651127
FL 19552860
IL 12882135
In [52]:
data[['population']].values
Out[52]:
array([[38332521],
       [26448193],
       [19651127],
       [19552860],
       [12882135]])
In [53]:
data['population'].values
Out[53]:
array([38332521, 26448193, 19651127, 19552860, 12882135])
In [54]:
data['population'].name
Out[54]:
'population'

When creating a DataFrame, Pandas conforms the indexes of the Series objects to a shared index, filling in NaN where it can't:

In [55]:
area = pd.Series({
    'CA': 423967, 
    'TX': 695662, 
    'NY': 141297,
    'FL': 170312, 
    'IL': 149995,
    'GA': 153910,
})
area
Out[55]:
CA    423967
TX    695662
NY    141297
FL    170312
IL    149995
GA    153910
dtype: int64
In [58]:
population
Out[58]:
CA    38332521
TX    26448193
NY    19651127
FL    19552860
IL    12882135
dtype: int64
In [56]:
data = pd.DataFrame({'population': population, 'area': area})
data
Out[56]:
population area
CA 38332521.0 423967
FL 19552860.0 170312
GA NaN 153910
IL 12882135.0 149995
NY 19651127.0 141297
TX 26448193.0 695662
In [59]:
data.index
Out[59]:
Index(['CA', 'FL', 'GA', 'IL', 'NY', 'TX'], dtype='object')
In [60]:
data.columns
Out[60]:
Index(['population', 'area'], dtype='object')

NaN¶

In [61]:
import numpy as np
In [62]:

Out[62]:
True
In [63]:
None is None
Out[63]:
True
In [64]:
np.nan is np.nan
Out[64]:
True
In [65]:
np.nan == np.nan, np.nan < np.nan, np.nan > np.nan
Out[65]:
(False, False, False)
In [66]:

Out[66]:
False
In [67]:
type(pd.NaT).mro()
Out[67]:
[pandas._libs.tslibs.nattype.NaTType,

 object]

To get a series back, we can simply access the DataFrame like a dict:

In [68]:

Out[68]:

FL    170312
GA    153910
IL    149995
NY    141297
TX    695662
Name: area, dtype: int64

data.area
Out[69]:

FL    170312
GA    153910
IL    149995
NY    141297
TX    695662
Name: area, dtype: int64

Indexing a DataFrame¶

It's clearer to use the .loc and .iloc indexers when updating DataFrames

In [73]:
data.loc['GA']
Out[73]:
population    10430000.0
area            153910.0
Name: GA, dtype: float64
In [75]:
data.loc['GA', 'population']
Out[75]:
10430000.0
In [76]:
data.loc['GA', 'population'] = 10.31e6
In [77]:
data
Out[77]:
population area
CA 38332521.0 423967
FL 19552860.0 170312
GA 10310000.0 153910
IL 12882135.0 149995
NY 19651127.0 141297
TX 26448193.0 695662
In [79]:
data['density'] = data.population / data.area
In [80]:
data
Out[80]:
population area density
CA 38332521.0 423967 90.413926
FL 19552860.0 170312 114.806121
GA 10310000.0 153910 66.987200
IL 12882135.0 149995 85.883763
NY 19651127.0 141297 139.076746
TX 26448193.0 695662 38.018740

Multi-dimensional slicing works, too.

In [81]:
data.loc['FL': 'IL', 'area']
Out[81]:
FL    170312
GA    153910
IL    149995
Name: area, dtype: int64

import re
dollar_comma = re.compile(r'[$,]')

def find_median(series):
    items = []
    for item in series:
        item = dollar_comma.sub('', item)
        item = float(item)
        items.append(item)
    items.sort()
    midpoint = (len(items) - 1) / 2
    if midpoint != int(midpoint):
        return (items[int(np.floor(midpoint))] + items[int(np.ceil(midpoint))]) / 2
    else:
        return items[int(midpoint)]
